@Andrzej
It was probably just a glitch. We express plenty of political opinions here that get through just fine.

And content moderation (not to be confused with censorship) is indeed used in Europe. I worked for a major Germann television broadcaster whose YouTube channel comments were constantly moderated for offensive content. It was one of my tasks to remove items that got past the filters and to restore items that were kicked out because of possible trigger words that were not used in an offensive way. When people accused us of censoring their remarks, we pointed out that the right to free speech does not obligate a media outlet to provide them with a platform.

@Teresa

Offensive, sure. But over here comments get quashed because, for example, they repeat a clue or answer that actually included an *adult* word in it! The outrage! Also, many words even slightly tinged with negativity will either delay a comment or cause it to never appear. You know the r-word that denotes something that is unthinkably unreasonable? I've never had a comment with it appear instantly, and my of them never did, at all.

You don't have to educate me on free speech, or as it is more commonly known in Europe, the freedom of expression. I know the obligations arising under it are aimed at the state (and largely negative rather than positive, and vertical rather than horizontal in effect). Still, that does not mean I am not entitled to not lightly accept a private entity censoring my speech, especially for inexplicable reasons. Being treated like a child annoyed me when I was an actual one, and these days I simply take it as offensive.

